</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
164 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
EX-REPORTER MACDOUGALL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I am concerned about the "rush to excuse" attitudes demonstrated in your 
article about MacDougall. Everyone from the dean of a graduate school of 
journalism to various editors of The Times and the Wall Street Journal seemed 
eager to make light of MacDougall's leftist magazine article, "Boring From 
Within the Bourgeois Press." 
</P>
<P>
And yet, this is a man who admits to being staunchly Marxist and claims to have 
for many years used his position as a Times and Journal reporter to secretly 
"help popularize radical ideas." MacDougall describes the use of techniques 
like making sure to seek out experts whose opinions he knew in advance would 
support his subversive thesis. These revelations are too hastily dismissed as 
"exaggerated" by the editors who worked with him. I question their willingness 
to face the truth just as I would question a nuclear plant manager's dismissive 
account of a "small accident." Serious implications require a serious response. 
</P>
<P>
ROBERT JUST 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
