<P>
THREAT CLOSES BEIJING ART EXHIBIT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BEIJING 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A major exhibition of avant-garde art, which opened amid controversy last week, 
was closed for a second time today after an anonymous letter writer threatened 
to blow up the gallery, artists said. 
</P>
<P>
Police barred the entrance to the prestigious China Art Gallery in central 
Beijing and authorities posted a sign saying the show was closed for two days 
for security reasons. The exhibition of pieces satirical, sexual and strange 
opened with a bang Feb. 5 when a woman pulled out a small pistol and fired two 
bullets into her work -- two glass telephone booths -- as an expression of 
"action art." 
</P>
</TEXT>
