<P>
2 MORE HELD IN JAPAN STOCK SCANDAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOKYO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Prosecutors today arrested two more top executives of companies at the center 
of a stock trading scandal, news reports said, bringing to six the number of 
people charged in the affair. 
</P>
<P>
Shunjiro Mamiya, the managing director of Recruit Co., a fast-growing business 
information conglomerate, and Seiichi Tateoka, the managing director of a real 
estate subsidiary, Recruit-Cosmos Co., were arrested on charges of violating 
the Securities and Exchange Law, television and news agency reports said. 
</P>
<P>
Today's arrests came two days after the parent company's founder, Hiromasa 
Ezoe, and three others were arrested on bribery charges. 
</P>
<P>
The arrests have shaken Japan's governing party and contributed to its loss in 
a special parliamentary election. Three Cabinet ministers and more than a dozen 
other prominent politicians and businessmen have resigned in the scandal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
