<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
ATLANTA URGED TO SEEK OLYMPICS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire service reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ATLANTA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The president of the International Olympic Committee encouraged Atlanta 
officials today to continue fighting to host the 1996 Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
Juan Antonio Samaranch was making his first visit to the city since it became 
the U.S. nominee for the 1996 Olympics. His schedule included a tour of the 
city's sports facilities as well as meetings with government and business 
leaders. 
</P>
<P>
"What can I say -- you will be one of the six candidates," he told a joint 
session of the Georgia Legislature. "But I think with public and private 
support, the beautiful Atlanta can be very, very strong." 
</P>
<P>
Samaranch was accompanied by Atlanta Mayor Andrew Young and Bob Helmick, 
president of the U.S. Olympic Committee. After a lunch with former Olympians 
from Georgia, he was to cut the ribbon to officially open the Atlanta 
Organizing Committee's office. 
</P>
<P>
Samaranch told the Legislature that he is often asked what a city must have to 
put together a winning package for the Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
His answer, he said, is always "the right people . . . and I hope and I think 
you have the right people now working and fighting to get the games for 
Atlanta." 
</P>
</TEXT>
